review_blob: Bottle pour..light black color..minimal head as expected..nose is roasted malts with toasted almond nutty presence..mouthfeel is good with lactose cream and some undertones of milk-dark chocolate..leaves some stout aftertaste that would be expected from a bigger abv offering, not a giant fan of the style but this is decent overall, more nutty roastiness than anything else..

Taster at iron hill Newark..mocha brown light caramel black..good head..nose is sweet coconut..barrel presence on nose..tad of rum..this is a winner..like the toasted coconut flavor profile with chocolate undertones..a tasty upgrade on regular pig iron porter..

Crowler via deciccos larchmont, crowler machine is brilliant, pours a light medium amber orange true to style..nice 1 finger frothy head..nose is really nice and jumps out with massive honeydew..mouthfeel follow suit with the honeydew cantaulope combo with some lemon lime zest with a bit of pleasing seltzer like spritz action..digging this a lot..highly enjoyable offering...

Pour at the source..draft offering light to medium orange hue..nose hasnt got much going on in terms of hop bomb or citrus forward..aroma is decent but nothing pops out as really distinguished..quite light bodied for the high abv..not really bitter or intense....decent

Short pour at the source..nice looking ipa but lighting wasnt great..looks like a light orange hue..aroma is quite good with all kinds of citrus grapefruit pithy qualities..blood orange as well..light mouthfeel..easy drinking, good flavor profile, digging the first offering from 2nd Story, really like short pour pricing option as well..solid citrus laden ipa that went well with bar snacks..

Bottle pour..bottled 3/16..pours a nice amber orange color..nose is pineapple juice and core with traces of dried mango..has some qualities of both lot 6 and 3 which is to be expected..not really a fan of pineapple ipa in general, this is pretty decent however..light bodied..easy drinking..nice new addition to EVo 12 oz lineup

can recently picked up at State Line..giving this a go even though not a fan of the Os or Eddie Murray..pours a golden orange amber color with slight haze and a solid 1 finger white frothy head..nose is great tropical fruit with papaya..mango..trace of pink grapefruit..this has got some potential..mouthfeel is very unique like the sorachi ace lemon presence as well with a trace of herbal presence and a touch of celery..really like the light combination between the citrus/herbs here..quite interesting offering that I would definitely drink a lot more of in both the spring and summertime..Union is putting out some very worthy offerings, keep putting em out, the cans/beer deScriptions/stories are classic as well..

Bottle pour..nice golden ale color..nose is yeast, banana..grist and a trace of those sunflower seeds..mouthfeel follows aroma..light to medium bodied with a bit of almond but butter on finish, has some decent depth for the 7%, not bad overall
beer_name: New Belgium /  Hof Ten Dormaal Lips of Faith - Golden Ale

review_blob: botle recently picked up in NY..intrigued by this label and deScription..medium golden color that appears a bit hazy..wow the nose is unique indeed..cross between kind bud, lemon/lime citrus rinds and juicy mandarin orange..mouthfeel is vibrant citrus for sure some wooden notes from the barrel..the wood has indeed infiltrated things here, mouthfeel has some serious depth and lingering quality to it, which is usually a sign of good things on my end..wintergreen flavors marry with the wood to leave an atypical taste profile for sure..definitely not your typical ipa..bitterness comes in pleasant waves..sneaky layered waves of depth and complexity.

Bomber pour a nice golden hue with a considerable fluffy white head..interesting nose..nice pilsener action..clean..flavorful..an interesting choice for an anniversary beer for sure, solid as usual from Victory

bottle picked up recently dated 2.2.16..pours a fairly dark golden orange with slight haze..nose is bready malt with intense dried apricots..and mango presence..mouthfeel is solid with plenty of punch from the hops tempered with malt sweetness..pine definitely plays into the taste profile with some floral notes as well..not heavy at all for the 8+ abv and the crazy ibu factor is not overwhelming..a nice dipa all around that does leave some sticky dank resin all around that lingers for a bit..tasty dipa..
beer_name: Singlecut Billy Full Stack Double IPA

review_blob: bottle recently scored on LI..dated 3.8.16..fresh as can be..pours a medium orange color with a nice 1 finger white head..wow is all that can be said from this nose..amazing citrus jumps out at you with overwhelming citrus..fresh orange puree..tangerine..all kinds of tropical fruits..guava..grapefruit..mango..passionfruit..mo is really sublime with all of the aforementioned citrus action with a pleasant coating of subdued bitterness and enjoyable ipa action..this is an absolutely terrific ipa and if you can find a better aroma and complex flavor profile on an ipa that isnt a 2xipa good luck with that...because this is sublime stuff..singlecut is putting out some great stuff..seek it out..it is worthy for sure...

draft offering at Teresas..nice golden color..good amount of carbonation..aroma of clove..spice mixture..light to medium bodied..quite enjoyable with food and packs a little bite with the 8% that is not overwhelming..tasty

bottle recently scored at Wegmans..pours a nice looking medium orange with a fluffy 1 finger fluffy head that dies down..damn the nose on this pretty great with all kinds of citrus action..mandarin orange..tangerine..orange zest..orange rind..meyer lemon as well..mouthfeel is top notch..light to medium bodied with all of the great citrus action up front with some grassiness on finish with just the pleasing, flavorful lingering punch of hoppy goodness...pretty amazing that this hides the 122 ibus so well since you would think this would be a bitter bomb..hop particles are all over the bottom of my teku glass..bottled 2.16..so quite fresh..like the raised lettering on the cool label..damn singlecut is pumping out some mighty tasty beers, I can see why they are indeed an up and coming brewery...very cool that there offerings are now in PA as well..looking forward to trying more from the beersmiths out of Astoria...delicious ipa..
Draft sample at teresas..light golden color..fresh brewed tea nose..light bodied mouthfeel..low abv..wasnt really feeling this..hoping for another hill farmstead draft offering..to no avail...
beer_name: Hill Farmstead Works of Love (Earl Grey Tea)

review_blob: sampler at Teresas..interesting beer..looks like angostura bitters in the color my god the nose is intense whiskey..very noticeable..trace of sugar..orange..in nose as well..flavor profile is strange to say the least..dont really drink old fashioned cocktails but this does come as more of a cocktail than a beer..the orange and the bitters are quite prevalent and the booze is very noticeable with the quite strong almost 13%..sweetness..pronounced spices thrown into the mix make this seem like some type of spice infused elixir rather than a beer..didnt really care for this..really glad I didnt get a full pour of this because I wouldnt have found it enjoyable really at all..whiskey lovers might find this more intriguing..

Thought I had rated this before..pours a solid 2 ipa orange..nose is apricot mango bomb..mouthfeel is much the same with good juicy citrus action..bitterness is well done at the end..solid citrus forward ipa

bomber bottled 1/16..pours glug glub sound with a dark black color and a slick creamy tan head..nose is really enjoyable with espresso beans, coffee beans, dark chocolate and some spice soaked vanilla..mouthfeel is even better than the nose with a creamy taste profile that really hides the abv well and is full of roasted goodness..the chocolate interplays nicely with the coffee and malt character..amazingly smooth, does have a hit of the abv on the final finish with some roasted nut presence as well..this reminds me of having the barrel aged sump at PBW a few years ago and being blown away by that offering, this is easily one of..if not the best coffee imperial stout out there and reaffirms my recollection of how good the barrel aged version was. worth seeking out and the high price point, awesome offering...

Bomber pour..nice orange color with 1 finger head..nose is fruity for sure with dried apricots..mango and tang aromas..light bodied with citrus bomb..not much bitterness..tang flavor is a bit excessive..decent but needs a tad more bitterness

recently scored can..been looking for this with not much luck..last 4 pack on the shelf..score..dated on bottom 1.28.16 so pretty fresh offering..pours a light orange ipa/dipa color with a massive frothy 3 finger white head..slight haze and particles that sink to bottom of glass..wow the nose here is absolutely wonderful and a sign of quality for sure..cantaloupe..honeydew..mango..lemon/lime zest..juicyfruit gum all rolled together with a trace of strawberry..mouthfeel lives up to the nose and is superb as well..this is not your run of the mill pilsener for sure..has qualities of an ipl/dipa/pilsener..reminds me of the Maine hop profile found in a few Foundation offerings..really enjoyed the layered waves of citrus involved to produce a velvety profile..fresh grass infused with strawberries combined with just the right amount of bitterness to keep palate intrigued and coming in at the perfect abv level..really impressive offering that is one of the better new beers I can remember having in some time...worth seeking out for sure..kudos for the 16 oz can offering as well..

2013 vintage..12 oz bottle pour..medium black color with a 1/2 finger mocha cream tan head that stays around..more carbonation than expected...nose is pretty goood with quality vanilla, charred wood..bitter chocolate...slight coffee...medium bodied taste profile yet a bit thinnner than expected after the hype on this and the nose..doesnt seem to be infected from the nose or the taste so pleased with that..coffee does come through more on taste profile with some cinnamon/clove essence..cream and cold press coffee come through as well to produce a decent coffee stout..dont get much of the barrel action from the taste, except maybe an initial hit of charred wood/vanilla..decent offering that seemed to have cellared ok, overall though I was expecting this to have more depth and complexity on the mouthfeel which seemed to be lacking...
beer_name: Central Waters Peruvian Morning Imperial Stout

review_blob: bottle pour..light orange color with minimal head..nose is screaming watermelon jolly ranchers..watermelon juice..rind of a watermelon..watermelon all the way..taste is just odd with cloyingsly sweet watermelon puree presence..not pleasant coating of the palate with even more watermelon..too sweet, not enough to keep the watermelon in check, not a big fan of watermelon beers, others may enjoy this more, best thing about this is the 10% is fairly disguised, and that I only got one of these bottles, not a fan of this one from Ballast Point
beer_name: Ballast Point Dorado Double IPA - Watermelon

review_blob: bottle pour..light medium orange color with 1/2 finger white head that does stay around..nose is the best part of this one with intense fresh pineapple juice, core..faint mango as well..light medium bodied easy to drink for sure..the flavor profile follows the nose closely with pineapple, citrus zest htting at first followed by some bitterness, bitterness is tame however..ok stuff but a bit put off by pineapple pine sol like combo that this seem to finish with, much prefer grapefruit sculpin over this any day of the week..worth trying however

can dated 2/15/16..fresh as can be..pours a tad lighter than expected dipa faint orange color..with a small head that reduces to a filmy coating thru out..nose is quite aromatic with abundant pineapple, mango/apricot, resiny goodness, citrus hop bomb..perhaps some tangerine as well..some real fruity citrusy gum that has about 5 different flavors thrown in..mouthfeel is ok a bit thinner than expected with such a complex nose..getting more of the apricot/tangerine bite at first with some heavy bitterness that coats the palate with resiny hop profile..medium bodied with some notice of the abv..nice to have another well crafted local dipa to be able to turn to, and love the fact that this is canned...worth seeking out for sure..good dipa..

bottle pour..amber caramel color with significant suspended particle..nose is caramelly malts for sure..biscuit like presence as well with rye bread in play as well..mouthfeel is decent with some nutty character reminiscent of a nutty brown ale that has some spruce hop notes..the 7.2% is noticeable on the linger, an interesting take on a lower abv american strong ale, ok, but nothing that is too exciting with this one

2014 draft on tap at 2SP Barleywine Event..pours a crimson red color..however hard to tell with bad light..nose is complex with vanilla, oak, toffee as billed, not getting any chocolate though..smokey bourbon mash really comes through with a deeper whiff..taste is really layered which is what I appreciate in offerings such as this..malty toffee, sweetness and bourbon heat shine through on the mouthfeel..the high abv is well hidden at first but then bam that bourbon heat and warmth provides a punch at the end..dont really enjoy barleywines that much but after having this all other barleywines dont reallly compare to the bourbon goodness present here..not much in terms of head or carbonation but to be expected from the style..quite enjoyable

Brewpub exclusive on Super Bowl sunday post polar bear plunge..wow..this is easily the best new beer I have had from Dogfish in many....many...many..many years..put this in 12 oz bottles and I would drink this frequently...everything about this just works..like the fruit...like the drinkable 7 abv..like the wild character to it...like the offering here and hopefully will be seeing more of this in the future somewhere? Just enough sourness, just enough fruit, just right!

Bottle pour..pops off nicely after cage n cork..pours a bit odd with appears to be some cork residue..light Amber color with small white filmy head that stays throughout..nose is pleasing with spices..cloves..coriander..faint banana fruit presence..bit of sweetness from the malt..undeniably smooth with very little trade of the high abv..does have some lingering warmth and complex depth..coats the palate with tripel goodness..went for the full effect pairing this with double cream Gouda..quite tasty together

Can recently picked up..first go at a canned mead..pours a very surprising light yellow hue..could easily pass for a white wine if one didnt know better from appearance..nose is crazy unique with the vanilla..cream soda..not getting the cocoa nibs on aroma..wow this reminds me of the smell of a dr Browns cream soda..mouthfeel is pleasing as well with some vinous notes and the bit of honey and yes some chocolate to round things out..this exceeded expectations and will warrant some future purchases from this outfit for sure..highly enjoyable stuff
beer_name: Charm City Retire by the Fire

review_blob: bottle pour..pours a yellow, golden light amber color..nose is honeydew..lemon/lime zest...some spruce as well..mouthfeel is nice and interesting with some qualities of a pilsner..easy drinking..light bodied, quite fruity with the melon coming through for sure, getting some of the cantaloupe as well..just a trace of bitterness on finish..not getting much pine here but enjoying the adundant fruit, nice mix of fruit, slight sweetness and a touch of bitter character as well..somewhat reminiscent of two brothers sidekick..would drink a lot of this in the summertime...

Can pour..canned 12.21.15 bb July 12 2016..pours a deceiving light to medium blonde with a small white creamy head that dissipates..nose is cream..sweet n low..faint roast coffee beans..taste is bleh all around..the sweetness is a bit overdone here..mouthfeel is a bit strange..not really digging this, comes across as a poor mans lower ABV version of carton regular coffee..definitely not going to start my day or end the day with this one anytime soon..sometimes the mad scientists miss, in my book this is such an instance..

Can 16 oz..pours a light yellow with active carbonation at front end..nose is ok with sour lemon heads and lemon rinds mostly with a bit of salt..mouthfeel is the same..easy drinking refreshing gose that seems to need a bit more sour action in my book..worth a try however
beer_name: Two Roads / Evil Twin Geyser Gose

review_blob: Bomber pour..pours a light orange with Rose tint..nose is fruit funk with raspberry..lemon rind..cherry..mouthfeel is light bodied has a nice intial tartness to it..slight wave of the chamomile rose hips..nicely done offering that has some sweetness and funk mixed in, this would go nicely in warmer summer weather

Bottle picked up at brewery a few years ago shared via a few for Jonas..a bit of a gusher..but the nose is crazy intense with booze oozing out all the way big time..bmedium brown color slight head.mouthfeel is Apple brandy all the way with the smoke peat in there as well..shit this is a flavor packed offering that hides the abv well..slight burnt caramel..oak presence..pretty tasty..
beer_name: Captain Lawrence Imperial Smoke from the Oak (Apple Brandy Barrel)

review_blob: Bottle picked up at sline..pours a medium black with mocha tan head..nose is very inviting with bitter cocoa..coffee and a bit of heat from pepper..mouthfeel is smooth..creamy..coats palate with chocolate goodness with a slight bit of heat..picking up the nutmeg now as well..mmmhm pretty solid offering here, I dont find the sweetness or the heat offensive..complement each other well..try it..its good
beer_name: Chris Banker / Insurgente / Stone Xocoveza Mocha Stout

review_blob: Bottle pours a light black color with small mocha head..initial aroma is pretty good but then seems to fade completely..getting an initial smack of the marshmallow and graham cracker with some chocolate as well..fairly light bodied for the high abv..smooth and creamy finish on palate, not as much depth as expected overall and the smores seems to almost fade completely from the initial awareness..was anticipating a little more from this, from the high price tag, had some milk stout qualities as well..ok

Draft sample at sline..tried two snorts to confirm the initial dissapointment..pours a medium brown with some hazy floaties...nose is so so with some sweetness mostly and sugary malt..really wanted to see some maple quality from things but not much here..dont love barleywines..but this was a bit not up to snuff from lawsons in my book...meh
beer_name: Otter Creek / Lawsons Finest Liquids Double or Nothing

review_blob: draft sampler at source..wow this is a complex offering to say the least..unreal amount of gin aroma oozing from the nose..mouthfeel provides an interesting mix of the pinot noir and gin aging and produces a nice warming sensation all around..this is strong stuff but shows you the care they are putting into these blends and eccentric offferings for sure...really enjoyed this one and definitely a memorable taste profile, aroma, all around depth...glad to have sampled this one

part of draft sampler..pours a light black color..crazy types of aroma coming from this one with wine..dark fruits..caffeine..mead..boozy syrupy interplay..this was really one insane concoction and an interesting sample for sure..mead drinkers would probably enjoy this more..not my cup of tea and found this probably the least enjoyable of all the OEC offerings..

part of draft sampler at source..rustic gose with grey sea salt coriander and pink peppercorns..blend of 20% spontaneously fermented ale is in play here..pours a light orange color..this is excellent..tart..sour..delicious..very easy to drink and well crafted..

part of draft sampler at the source..pours a bit flatter than anticipated..this one was served at 42 degrees so slightly surprised by the limited carbonation..the vinous notes from the syrah/chardonnay barrels come through on the nose for sure..however beyond that not much intrigue here on this one, not the biggest fan of this style however...

draft sample at the source..part of stellar flight..slight saltiness for sure..light bodied..spritzy mouthfeel..peppery profile..not getting as much from the eccentric barreling in this one as prior gin/pinot noir barrel..a solid gose all around

Bomber poured many ways pre NYE..bottle from 2013..pours a vinous color with an unreal sour cherry aroma..nose is complex, tart, earthy, sour..all in one..mouthfeel is very complex and the tart cherries shine through..bit of pucker action from the fruit..but is kept in check..the wood adds depth..this is a nice take on the style and was enjoyed by all who sampled..best offering I can remember having from this outfit..

Bottle split several ways..small sample size but looking forward to another WW offering..pours your standard light orange color..nose is great with all kinds of citrus abound..mouthfeel is great..hides the ABV very well..like the citrus character.clean profile with just proper amount of bitterness..very good dipa, I was happy to sample
beer_name: Wicked Weed Freak Of Nature Double IPA

review_blob: Bomber pour..medium black color with substantial cream colored mocha head..nose is solid for the style with definite coffee..espresso..coming through..bit of chocolate..both dark and milk..mouthfeel is sublime on this with overwhelming smoothness..getting the chocolate for sure...oats..coffee..no trace of the 10 ABV until well after the fact, warming sensation appears much later on..has some milkshake taste characteristics..this is a very well put together RIS and it proves that barrel aging isnt always necessary for a complex high octane stout..seek it out, as usual EVO large bottle formats dont disappoint and are worth the $
beer_name: Evolution Craft Rise Up Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: draft offering at the source..this was first up and after this one I knew that this place was legit for sure..nose is unreal..everything a true white wild ale wishes it could be..easily the best take on a white belgian style I have tried to date..this has it all light bodied..yet full of complexity..juicy characteristics..lemon tart and lemon peels abound..getting some of the ginger spice but kept in check..finishes nice and the lactobaccilus is extremely well done..great offering from a place that is doing some very impressive things...
Growler sample..pours a brownish red like hue..nose does have that rye spiciness..taste follows suit..pretty interesting but not nearly as solid as most of cartons offerings

Black pour from bottle..not the freshest bottle so might impact things..small tan mocha head..nose is toasted nuts,black licorice, anise, rye grain..taste follows suit..interesting..comes across as a mix between a porter and black ipa.pretty smooth nice flavor..some spice from the rye on the end with a solid lingering finish that has that chocolate presence for sure..would be great with chocolate sweets..

can pour..black color with mocha head..nose is nice with toasted coconut..vanilla..cream..reminisent of aroma from certain sun tan oils..really solid lacing all around..creamy mouthfeel..nice texture with the coconut produces a nutty..roasty flavor profile that is smooth and full of coconut for sure..pretty tasty but i couldnt really drink more than 1 of these however in a row..
beer_name: Oskar Blues / Shamrock Death By Coconut

review_blob: picked up recently from a black friday visit up in ny during thanksgiving while scoring some GIBCBS...didnt realize how rare this would be until after the fact..pours a medium dark brown with minimal head.holy shit the aroma on this is pure bourbon..and yes good bourbon not the cheap stuff..nose is all barrel..with vanilla..oak..warmth all shining through..really suprised by the mouthfeel on this because for such an intense bourbon smell..the overall mouthfeel is fairly, tame, not hot, intense or offensive in any way...damn this was an interesting offering to say the least, I should have picked up another bottle to lay down for some time..oh well..those who like good bourbon seek this out, those who dont buy it anyway because this is rare stuff that will surely peak the interests of those who like bourbon barrel aged stuff...l chaim!
